A Pose-to-Performance Analyzer uses computer vision and deep learning to track skeletal joint positions (such as shoulders, hips, and knees) in real-time. It maps body movements to biomechanical data, translating raw video into actionable metrics like joint angles, range of motion, and movement symmetry


Core Use CasesSports & Athletics: Tracks biomechanics to optimize athletic technique and performance (e.g., analyzing a golf swing or a runner's stride).Physical Therapy & Rehab: Monitors joint angles to ensure patients perform home exercises correctly, tracking recovery without expensive lab equipment.Fitness & Posture Correction: Provides real-time audio and visual feedback on form, such as squat depth or forward head posture.Injury Prevention: Flags risky movement patterns, such as improper knee alignment before an injury 
How It WorksKeypoint Detection: Uses AI models to identify specific body joints.Skeleton Mapping: Connects the keypoints into a 2D or 3D skeletal structure.Data Analysis: Measures angles, velocities, and acceleration across frames to evaluate performance

